  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        The preimage of a set <m>B\subseteq Y</m> under a function <m>f:X\to Y</m> is the set
        <me>
          f\inv(B)=\set{x\in X:f(x)\in B}\text{.}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        A function is continuous if the preimage of every open set is open.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Inverse function theorem: A continuous function of a single variable <m>f:A\to\bb R</m> is invertible on its image if and only if it is strictly monotonic.
        If <m>f</m> is continuously differentiable on an interval <m>I</m> and <m>f'(x)\neq 0</m> for each <m>x\in I</m>, then <m>f\inv</m> is continuously differentiable on <m>f(I)</m> and
        <me>
          (f\inv)'(y)=\dfrac{1}{f'(x)}\text{.}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        In multiple dimensions, the Jacobian needs to be nonzero, and it guarantees the existence of a unique solution.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If we drop the assumption that <m>f'</m> is continuous, <m>f</m> may not be invertible.
        Great example is
        <me>
          f(x)=x+2x^{2}\sin\tfrac1x
        </me>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>f'</m> is invertible, it maps open sets to open sets (itâ€™s an open map).
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Implicit function theorem: If <m>f(x,y)</m> is a function that is continuously differentiable in a neighborhood of <m>(x_{0},y_{0})</m>, and <m>\pdv{f}{y}(x_{0},y_{0})\neq 0</m>, then there exists a unique differentiable function <m>\phi</m> such that <m>y_{0}=\phi(x_{0})</m> and <m>f(x,\phi(x))=0</m> in a neighborhood of <m>x_{0}</m>.
        We have:
        <me>
          \dv{y}{x}=\phi'(x)=-\frac{\partial f/\partial x}{\partial f/\partial y}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
